<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910709-0088</DOCNO><DOCID>910709-0088.</DOCID><HL>   New Indictment Adds   Charges in Fraud Case   On Medical Insurance</HL><DATE>07/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)INSURANCE (INS)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A federal grand jury handed up a newindictment against health clinic operator Michael Smushkevichand three associates that names eight new defendants and morethan triples to 175 the number of charges in a $1 billionmedical-insurance fraud scheme.   The indictment, which supersedes three earlier ones, isthe first to name Mr. Smushkevich's brother, David. He is afugitive from parole and probation terms stemming from a 1987conviction on Medicare kickback charges and is in custody inAmsterdam pending extradition, according to the U.S.Attorney's office here.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;This is a horrific exercise in prosecutorial abuse,&quot; saidJim Barber, a Salt Lake City attorney representing MichaelSmushkevich. Mr. Smushkevich &quot;isn't guilty of fraud. . . .This is really a civil case related to {insurance claim}methodologies rather than a crime,&quot; he said.   The government alleges that doctors and technicians at theSmushkevich clinics in Southern California submitted as muchas $1 billion in false claims to insurance companies and tothe Department of Defense Civilian Health and Medical Programfor the Uniformed Services, known as Champus.   The defendants, including the Smushkevich brothers, theirwives, and certain clinic doctors and managers, solicited thepublic by telephone with promises of &quot;free&quot; or &quot;nominal cost&quot;examinations or diagnostic tests, the indictment charges.Patients signed forms assigning to the clinics the right toinsurance benefits. Bills were submitted to insurers falselyindicating that the tests had been prescribed by a doctor,prosecutors said.   The superseding indictment includes new charges, includingmoney laundering and violations of the Racketeer Influencedand Corrupt Organizations Act. Previous indictments hadcharged the defendants with mail fraud and conspiracy.</TEXT></DOC>